			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Towards User-Friendly Projectional Editors</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MarkusVölter.html">Markus Völter</a>, <a href="../profile/JanetSiegmund.html">Janet Siegmund</a>, <a href="../profile/ThorstenBerger.html">Thorsten Berger</a>, <a href="../profile/BerndKolb.html">Bernd Kolb</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_3">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_3</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It focuses on language workbench/editor technology for projectional editing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> A major motivation is enabling language extension and composition through editor support.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> It explicitly targets user-friendliness and evaluates/argues about usability issues in projectional editors.
</li></ul></li></ul>
